<DOC><DOCNO> AP890910-0052 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-10-89 1746EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-10 0463</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0474</SECOND><HEAD>A Taste of Winter in the Northwest</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Cold air pushed across the Rockies onto the Plains on Sunday,keeping daytime temperatures as low as the 30s and spreading snowand rain, and thunderstorms were scattered across parts of the East.   The unseasonably cool weather was caused by a large high pressurearea centered over central Alberta.   Billings, Mont., had a record low of 33, and both Boise, Idaho,and Yakima, Wash., tied their records of 36.   Early afternoon temperatures were only in the 30s and 40s Sundayover the northern Rockies and northern high Plains.   The cold air along with an upper air disturbance over southernSaskatchewan produced low clouds and light rain across the northernPlains and Nebraska.   Snow fell across sections of Montana, with 3 inches overnight atFairfield and an inch at Lewiston.   From 3 to 6 inches of snow was expected to accumulate during thenight over the Big Horn Mountains west of Sheridan, Wyo.   By contrast, hot, humid weather covered much of the AtlanticCoast states and the Southeast with temperatures in the 90s into NewEngland. Burlington, Vt., tied its record at 90 degrees.   Thunderstorms with locally heavy rain were scattered over centraland southeast Texas. Mexia got 3.91 inches of rain Sunday morning.   Thunderstorms also were scattered ahead of a cold front from thelower Mississippi Valley across the Tennessee Valley and the centralAppalachians to western New York state. Leland, Miss., received 3.31inches of rain during the morning.   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 34degrees at Cody, Wyo., to 100 at Palm Springs, Calif. Sunday's lowin the Lower 48 states was 23 at West Yellowstone, Mont.   For Monday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecastfrom northern New England across the middle Atlantic Coast and muchof the Appalachians into the Tennessee Valley. Scattered showers andthunderstorms also were forecast from the lower and middleMississippi Valley to the central Plains and Oklahoma into Colorado.Showers were forecast from the upper Mississippi Valley across thenorthern Plains into Wyoming. Snow was forecast over the mountainsof Wyoming and the Black Hills of South Dakota. Scatteredthunderstorms were forecast over Florida.   Highs in the 40s were predicted over northern Wyoming and westernSouth Dakota; in the 50s and 60s from Idaho across the centralRockies, much of the northern and central Plains and the upperMississippi Valley to the upper Great Lakes; in the 90s from thesouthern Atlantic Coast and Florida across the Gulf Coast regioninto southern and eastern Texas, as well as over interior valleys ofCalifornia; between 100 and 110 over the desert Southwest; and inthe 70s and 80s across much of the rest of the nation.</TEXT></DOC>